            <section id="overview">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    The <strong>DocumentationRoleAccess</strong> model (Comserv/lib/Comserv/Model/Schema/Ency/Result/DocumentationRoleAccess.pm) 
                    provides a database schema for managing role-based access control (RBAC) to documentation sections in the Comserv application. It is a DBIx::Class Result class that supports:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Role-based access rules for documentation sections</li>
                    <li>Pattern-based matching (wildcards) for flexible path matching</li>
                    <li>Grant and deny rules (can_access boolean flag)</li>
                    <li>Unique constraints preventing duplicate role+pattern combinations</li>
                    <li>Timestamp tracking for audit trails</li>
                    <li>Helper methods for access determination and pattern matching</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    DocumentationRoleAccess enables administrators to control which user roles can view specific documentation sections, 
                    supporting security models where sensitive documentation (admin guides, internal procedures) is hidden from non-admin users.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section id="schema">
                <h2>Database Schema & Fields</h2>
                
                <h3>Table: documentationroleaccess</h3>
                <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Store role-based access control rules for documentation sections</p>
                <p><strong>Primary Key:</strong> id (auto-increment)</p>
                <p><strong>Unique Constraints:</strong> (role, doc_section_pattern) - one rule per role+pattern</p>
                
                <table class="table table-bordered">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Field Name</th>
                        <th>Data Type</th>
                        <th>Nullable</th>
                        <th>Default</th>
                        <th>Description</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>id</td>
                        <td>INTEGER</td>
                        <td>NO</td>
                        <td>auto_increment</td>
                        <td>Primary key - auto-generated access rule ID</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>role</td>
                        <td>VARCHAR(100)</td>
                        <td>NO</td>
                        <td>REQUIRED</td>
                        <td>User role (e.g., 'admin', 'developer', 'editor', 'user') - part of UNIQUE constraint</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>doc_section_pattern</td>
                        <td>VARCHAR(255)</td>
                        <td>NO</td>
                        <td>REQUIRED</td>
                        <td>Path pattern with wildcards (e.g., 'Documentation/system/*', 'Documentation/admin/*') - part of UNIQUE constraint</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>can_access</td>
                        <td>BOOLEAN</td>
                        <td>NO</td>
                        <td>1 (true)</td>
                        <td>Access grant: 1=allow access, 0=deny/restrict access (default: 1=ALLOW)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>created_at</td>
                        <td>TIMESTAMP</td>
                        <td>NO</td>
                        <td>CURRENT_TIMESTAMP</td>
                        <td>Timestamp when rule was created (auto-set)</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </section>

            <section id="access-control">
                <h2>Access Control Model</h2>
                
                <h3>Role-Based Rules</h3>
                <p>DocumentationRoleAccess uses a simple role-based model with allow/deny flags:</p>
                
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Role:</strong> Target user role (e.g., 'admin', 'developer', 'editor', 'user')</li>
                    <li><strong>Pattern:</strong> Documentation path pattern (supports wildcards *)</li>
                    <li><strong>can_access:</strong> Boolean flag: true=ALLOW, false=DENY</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Example Access Rules</h3>
                <table class="table table-bordered">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Role</th>
                        <th>Pattern</th>
                        <th>can_access</th>
                        <th>Effect</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>admin</td>
                        <td>Documentation/*</td>
                        <td>✅ 1 (TRUE)</td>
                        <td>Admins can access ALL documentation</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>developer</td>
                        <td>Documentation/system/*</td>
                        <td>✅ 1 (TRUE)</td>
                        <td>Developers can access system docs</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>developer</td>
                        <td>Documentation/admin/*</td>
                        <td>❌ 0 (FALSE)</td>
                        <td>Developers CANNOT access admin docs</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>user</td>
                        <td>Documentation/public/*</td>
                        <td>✅ 1 (TRUE)</td>
                        <td>Regular users can access public docs only</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>user</td>
                        <td>Documentation/*</td>
                        <td>❌ 0 (FALSE)</td>
                        <td>Users cannot access other sections</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <h3>Typical Access Hierarchy</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Admin:</strong> Full access to all documentation</li>
                    <li><strong>Developer:</strong> Access to technical documentation, code examples, system guides (but not admin/internal)</li>
                    <li><strong>Editor:</strong> Access to content they manage, unable to view admin sections</li>
                    <li><strong>User:</strong> Access to public documentation only</li>
                </ol>
            </section>

            <section id="pattern-matching">
                <h2>Pattern Matching & Wildcards</h2>
                
                <h3>Wildcard Support</h3>
                <p>The doc_section_pattern field supports simple wildcard matching using * (asterisk):</p>
                
                <h3>Pattern Examples</h3>
                <table class="table table-bordered">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Pattern</th>
                        <th>Matches</th>
                        <th>Does NOT Match</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Documentation/*</td>
                        <td>Documentation/controllers, Documentation/models, Documentation/system</td>
                        <td>Documentation/system/advanced, Documentation (no slash)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>Documentation/system/*</td>
                        <td>Documentation/system/admin, Documentation/system/config</td>
                        <td>Documentation/system/admin/advanced, Documentation/models</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Documentation/admin*</td>
                        <td>Documentation/admin, Documentation/admin_guide, Documentation/admin/settings</td>
                        <td>Documentation/system/admin, Documentation/user</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.12);">
                        <td>*admin*</td>
                        <td>Documentation/admin, admin_guide, system/admin (broad match)</td>
                        <td>(matches anything with 'admin' substring)</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <h3>Pattern Matching Implementation</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>How matches_doc_path() works:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>my $rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->find($id);

# Pattern: 'Documentation/system/*'
# Input: 'Documentation/system/admin/users'
# Converts to: '^Documentation/system/.*$'
# Result: MATCHES

if ($rule->matches_doc_path('Documentation/system/advanced')) {
    # Access determination based on can_access flag
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Pattern Matching Details</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Wildcards (*) are converted to .* (regex any characters)</li>
                    <li>Patterns must match the entire path (anchored with ^ and $)</li>
                    <li>Matching is case-sensitive</li>
                    <li>No regex escaping needed; patterns are literal paths with * wildcards only</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="access-grants">
                <h2>Access Grants & Denials</h2>
                
                <h3>can_access Flag</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>can_access = 1 (TRUE):</strong> ALLOW - Role CAN access documentation sections matching the pattern</li>
                    <li><strong>can_access = 0 (FALSE):</strong> DENY/RESTRICT - Role CANNOT access documentation sections matching the pattern</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Decision Logic</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>Check if role can access a documentation path:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code># Query all rules for a role
my @rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    role => 'developer'
})->all;

my $doc_path = 'Documentation/system/advanced';
my $can_access = 0;

foreach my $rule (@rules) {
    if ($rule->matches_doc_path($doc_path)) {
        $can_access = $rule->grants_access();
        last; # First matching rule determines access
    }
}

if ($can_access) {
    print "Access GRANTED\n";
} else {
    print "Access DENIED\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section id="api-methods">
                <h2>API Methods & Helpers</h2>
                
                <h3>Standard DBIx::Class Methods</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>Creating Access Rules:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>my $rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
    role => 'developer',
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/system/*',
    can_access => 1  # Allow access
});

my $deny_rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
    role => 'user',
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/admin/*',
    can_access => 0  # Deny access
});</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>Retrieving Rules:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>my $rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->find(1);

my @dev_rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    role => 'developer'
})->all;

my @allow_rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    can_access => 1
})->all;

my @deny_rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    can_access => 0
})->all;</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>Updating Rules:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>$rule->update({
    can_access => 0  # Change from allow to deny
});

$rule->doc_section_pattern('Documentation/admin/*');
$rule->update;</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Helper Methods</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>matches_doc_path($doc_path):</strong> Check if path matches rule pattern</p>
                    <pre><code>if ($rule->matches_doc_path('Documentation/system/admin')) {
    print "Pattern matches this path\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <p><strong>grants_access():</strong> Get access grant boolean</p>
                    <pre><code>if ($rule->grants_access) {
    print "Access is ALLOWED\n";
} else {
    print "Access is DENIED\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section id="examples">
                <h2>Usage Examples</h2>
                
                <h3>Example 1: Create Admin Access Rule</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <pre><code>my $admin_rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
    role => 'admin',
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/*',
    can_access => 1
});

print "Created rule: " . $admin_rule->role . " -> " . $admin_rule->doc_section_pattern . "\n";</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Example 2: Set Up Developer Permissions</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <pre><code>my @dev_permissions = (
    { pattern => 'Documentation/models/*', access => 1 },
    { pattern => 'Documentation/controllers/*', access => 1 },
    { pattern => 'Documentation/system/*', access => 1 },
    { pattern => 'Documentation/admin/*', access => 0 }
);

foreach my $perm (@dev_permissions) {
    $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
        role => 'developer',
        doc_section_pattern => $perm->{pattern},
        can_access => $perm->{access}
    });
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Example 3: Check Access for User</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <pre><code>sub can_user_access_doc {
    my ($schema, $user_role, $doc_path) = @_;
    
    my @rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
        role => $user_role
    })->all;
    
    foreach my $rule (@rules) {
        if ($rule->matches_doc_path($doc_path)) {
            return $rule->grants_access;
        }
    }
    
    return 0; # Default deny if no matching rule
}

# Usage
if (can_user_access_doc($schema, 'developer', 'Documentation/system/config')) {
    print "Access GRANTED\n";
} else {
    print "Access DENIED\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Example 4: Update Access Rule</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <pre><code>my $rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    role => 'developer',
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/internal/*'
})->first;

if ($rule) {
    $rule->update({
        can_access => 1  # Grant access to internal docs
    });
    print "Updated: developers now have access to internal docs\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <h3>Example 5: Query All Rules for Role</h3>
                <div style="background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.15); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
                    <pre><code>my @editor_rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    role => 'editor'
})->all;

print "Access Rules for Editor Role:\n";
foreach my $rule (@editor_rules) {
    my $status = $rule->grants_access ? 'ALLOW' : 'DENY';
    print "  " . $rule->doc_section_pattern . " -> $status\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section id="troubleshooting">
                <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
                
                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <h3>Issue 1: Duplicate Role+Pattern Combination</h3>
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Error "Duplicate entry" when creating access rule</p>
                    <p><strong>Cause:</strong> (role, doc_section_pattern) has UNIQUE constraint</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>my $rule = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->find_or_create({
    role => 'developer',
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/system/*'
});

# Update existing rule
$rule->update({ can_access => 1 });</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <h3>Issue 2: Pattern Matching Not Working</h3>
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> matches_doc_path() returns false when expecting true</p>
                    <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Regex anchors require full match; partial paths fail</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code># CORRECT: Full path from root
$rule->matches_doc_path('Documentation/system/advanced'); # OK

# INCORRECT: Partial path
$rule->matches_doc_path('system/advanced'); # Returns false

# Pattern: 'Documentation/system/*'
# Must match entire path with anchors ^...$</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <h3>Issue 3: Access Denied When Should Be Allowed</h3>
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> User can't access documentation despite rule being created</p>
                    <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Multiple rules for same role; first match wins (check ordering)</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code>my @rules = $schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->search({
    role => 'user'
}, {
    order_by => 'created_at'  # Check which rule matches first
})->all;

# Debug: Print all rules and test path
foreach my $rule (@rules) {
    my $match = $rule->matches_doc_path('Documentation/admin');
    print $rule->doc_section_pattern . " -> " . $match . "\n";
}</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <h3>Issue 4: Wildcard Pattern Syntax Error</h3>
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Pattern with regex metacharacters (., +, ?, [, ]) fails</p>
                    <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Patterns expect simple wildcards only; no regex</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code># CORRECT: Simple wildcards only
doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/system/*'
doc_section_pattern => '*admin*'

# INCORRECT: Regex syntax
doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/system/.*'  # Wrong: use * not .*
doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/(admin|user)' # Wrong: no groups</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="alert alert-warning">
                    <h3>Issue 5: No Rules Created for New Role</h3>
                    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> New user role has no access control rules; default behavior</p>
                    <p><strong>Cause:</strong> No rules exist; access defaults to DENY</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
                    <pre><code># Create default rules for new role
my $new_role = 'viewer';

# Grant public access
$schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
    role => $new_role,
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/public/*',
    can_access => 1
});

# Deny restricted access
$schema->resultset('DocumentationRoleAccess')->create({
    role => $new_role,
    doc_section_pattern => 'Documentation/admin/*',
    can_access => 0
});</code></pre>
                </div>
            </section>

